# SimHub Development Rules

## Dashboard UI

- Prefer **HTML/JavaScript** for dashboard UI over native Windows/Dash Studio WPF objects.
- Dashboards run in a real browser — use full **ES6+** JavaScript (async/await, fetch, WebSocket, arrow functions).
- Do NOT confuse browser JS with SimHub's Jint formula engine (ES5.1, `$prop()`, `root[]`). These are completely separate contexts.

## Plugin Development

- Plugins target **.NET Framework 4.8** (not .NET Core / .NET 5+).
- Reference SDK demos at `C:\Program Files (x86)\SimHub\PluginSdk`.
- Use `Init()` for AddProperty/AddAction and WebSocket server startup.
- `DataUpdate()` runs at ~60 Hz — keep it fast (< 1/60s).

## Plugin ↔ Dashboard Communication

- Use **Fleck** (TcpListener-based WebSocket library) for the plugin server. Do NOT use `HttpListener` — it requires Windows administrator privileges.
- Plugin broadcasts telemetry JSON to connected WebSocket clients from `DataUpdate`.
- Dashboard sends action JSON messages via WebSocket when buttons are clicked.
- Dashboard HTML is served by **SimHub's built-in HTTP server** (port 8888) from `<SimHub>\Web\sim-steward-dash\`, not by the plugin itself.
- **Fleck must bind to `0.0.0.0`** (all interfaces) so LAN clients can reach the WebSocket. Binding to `127.0.0.1` blocks any browser that opens the dashboard via the machine's LAN IP.
- The dashboard uses `window.location.hostname` to build the WebSocket URL, so it always targets the correct host regardless of whether it is opened locally or from the LAN.
- **SimHub owns `/` and `/Web/`**: SimHub's C# router intercepts these routes before the filesystem — static files at `Web\index.html` are never served. The only reachable URL is `http://<host>:8888/Web/sim-steward-dash/index.html`.

## iRacing Shared Memory

- Access iRacing data directly via **IRSDKSharper** (NuGet), NOT through SimHub's limited `GameRawData` (which only exposes `drivers01` / `session01`).
- **Primary use case**: Catching incidents and unfair events that happen to the **driving user**. In replay mode, capture the full telemetry stack.
- **ADMIN LIMITATION**: Both `ResultsPositions[].Incidents` and `DriverInfo.Drivers[].CurDriverIncidentCount` in session YAML stay 0 for other drivers during a **live race** unless the user is **session admin**. During **replay** (`SimMode == "replay"`) or after **checkered** (`SessionState >= 5`), all-driver data is available.
- **Incident point type = delta value**: delta 1 = 1x off-track, delta 2 = 2x wall/spin, delta 4 = 4x heavy contact (paved). Dirt racing: heavy contact = 2x. Check `WeekendInfo.Category`.
- **Quick-succession rule**: iRacing promotes lower→higher (2x spin then 4x contact = delta 4 only, not 6).
- **Incident detection**: `DriverInfo.Drivers[].CurDriverIncidentCount` from session YAML (fires on each `SessionInfoUpdate`). Replay scan uses `RpySrch_NextIncident` to seek to each incident frame and read YAML deltas + telemetry arrays.
- At **16x replay speed**: TickRate stays 60 Hz (real-clock). YAML batches incidents at high speed.
- Use `IRacingSdk.UpdateInterval = 1` for maximum polling fidelity.
- The SDK broadcast API supports `RpySrch_NextIncident` / `RpySrch_PrevIncident` — expose as "Jump to Incident" buttons.
- **iRacing replay hotkeys (official)**: [Keyboard Shortcuts: Replay / Camera Controls](https://www.iracing.com/keyboard-shortcuts-replay-camera-controls/) — **Next incident** `Ctrl`+**Numpad 3**; **Previous incident** `Ctrl`+**Numpad 1**.
- **Unverified**: That page does not say whether next/previous incident is **session-wide** or **scoped to the car selected in the replay UI**; confirm in-client if it matters.
- **SDK vs hotkeys**: `HandleReplaySearch` calls `_irsdk.ReplaySearch(mode)` with no car index (session-level API hint) — not proof of in-game behavior when another car is focused.
- Always call `_irsdk.Stop()` in `End()` to clean up background threads.

## Deployment & Testing

- **No deploy without 100% passing tests.** The `deploy.ps1` script enforces this: build must succeed, `dotnet test` must pass (if test projects exist), and post-deploy scripts in `tests/` must exit 0.
- **Retry-once-then-stop rule**: when a test or build fails, the agent gets **one** additional attempt to fix and rerun. If it fails again, **hard stop** — do not keep iterating. Either halt the deploy entirely (if downstream work depends on it) or skip and move on to the next independent task.
- **Linter checks** (`ReadLints`) on edited files must show 0 new errors before committing or deploying.
- Tests include: `dotnet build` (0 errors), `dotnet test` (0 failures), `tests/*.ps1` scripts (exit 0, `PASS:` lines only), and linter checks on changed files.
- See `.cursor/skills/simsteward-deploy/SKILL.md` for the full deploy workflow and test phase details.

## Community References

- [SimHubPropertyServer](https://github.com/pre-martin/SimHubPropertyServer) — primary architecture reference (TCP server in plugin + action triggering).
- [Fleck](https://github.com/statianzo/Fleck) — WebSocket server library for .NET.
- [IRSDKSharper](https://github.com/mherbold/IRSDKSharper) — high-performance C# iRacing SDK wrapper (session info + telemetry threads, YAML parsing, replay event system).
- [RaceAdmin](https://github.com/GameDotPlay/RaceAdmin) — reference for all-driver incident tracking from iRacing SDK with delta detection and caution logic.

## Loki logging

New code that handles external input or produces output must emit structured logs (`action_dispatched` / `action_result`, lifecycle, incidents — never per-tick logs in `DataUpdate()` without a throttle, never full snapshot blobs). Full taxonomy and limits: [docs/GRAFANA-LOGGING.md](docs/GRAFANA-LOGGING.md) and `.cursor/skills/grafana-loki-observability/SKILL.md`.

## Development cadence

- **Small changes only.** Each task should touch the minimum number of files needed.
  Prefer one logical change per editing session — one new class, one modified method,
  one config file. Large sweeping changes hide bugs and make rollback hard.
- **Check after every change.** After each edit: run `dotnet build` (0 errors required),
  run `ReadLints` on changed files (0 new errors), and if the change touches runtime
  behaviour, do a quick deploy-and-test cycle before moving to the next task.
- **Commit at milestones.** A milestone is any point where the build is green, tests pass,
  and the change is independently useful or safe to ship (e.g. "LokiSink compiles and
  no-ops when unconfigured", "all action handlers emit structured logs", "local stack
  confirmed pushing data"). Do not accumulate multiple milestones in one commit.
  All executed plans and agent commands that change the repo must be established in a
  commit (see [commit-after-execution](.cursor/rules/commit-after-execution.mdc)).
- **One todo at a time.** Mark a todo `in_progress` before starting it. Do not start the
  next todo until the current one is committed and green.
- **Retry-once-then-stop rule still applies.** If a build or test fails after one fix
  attempt, hard stop — do not keep iterating blindly.
